,Recommended,427820,29380768,Posted: 20 January,all,nerdfury,"I purchased Hitman:GO because I adore board games and puzzles, so this review is coming from someone who isn’t familiar with the Hitman franchise. For the most part, Hitman:GO was an enjoyable turn-based puzzling experience. I loved the board piece visuals, the sleek and minimal interface, and how the game would gradually introduce trickier enemies to evade and obstacles/helpful items as I progressed.  I do, however, have 2 design flaws I want to stress to all potential buyers:1) There are different level packs that you unlock by completing objectives. Some objectives, such as “don’t kill any enemies” or “don’t kill any dogs”, make sense. The “complete the level in X turns or less” objective, however, is thoroughly asinine without a turn counter. I don’t consider myself a spoiled gamer by any means, but I think it’s rather ludicrous that a person should have to count 20+ turns in their head (while also trying to solve the puzzle at hand) in order to complete an objective.2) Positioning is key in a turn-based puzzler where you need to evade your enemies. However, in some levels, certain areas of the board (and your options to move) are obscured by walls. Sure, I can use the right mouse button to reposition the camera, but this is VERY clunky.TLDR;Hitman:GO is a good turn-based board game. Design flaws prevent it from being a great game in the puzzle genre. I recommend it to board game and puzzle lovers, but with reservations."
